BEGIN_PGML Determine if the table below could represent a linear or exponential function. Then find a formula for the function the table describes.
>> [@DataTable( [ [[PGML('[`x`]'), halign => 'l|', cellcss => 'border-bottom: 1px solid; border-right: 1px solid; ',], [PGML('0'), halign => 'l|', cellcss => 'border-bottom: 1px solid; border-right: 1px solid; ',], [PGML('1'), halign => 'l|', cellcss => 'border-bottom: 1px solid; border-right: 1px solid; ',], [PGML('2'), halign => 'l|', cellcss => 'border-bottom: 1px solid; border-right: 1px solid; ',], [PGML('3'), cellcss => 'border-bottom: 1px solid; ',], ], [[PGML('[`f(x)`]'), halign => 'l|', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], [PGML('[$a]'), halign => 'l|', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], [PGML('[$f1]'), halign => 'l|', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], [PGML('[$f2]'), halign => 'l|', cellcss => 'border-right: 1px solid; ',], PGML('[$f3]'), ], ], align => 'lllll', center => 0, );@]* <<
The table describes a(n) [_]{$ans1}{5} function with formula
[`f(x) =`] [_]{$ans2}{12}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION There is not a constant difference between function values, so we try multplication instead. After computing [`[$f1]/[$a]=[$b$]\text{,}`] we check that it is the consistent multiple between function values:
[```[$f1] * [$b] = [$f2]```]
[```[$f2] * [$b] = [$f3]```]
So we conclude that this table could represent an exponential function. The initial value is [`f(0)=[$a]`] and we found [`b=[$b]\text{,}`] so [`f(x)=[$ans2]\text{.}`]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
